Balanerpeton woodi is the oldest species, having been present over 330 million years ago during the Temnodontiformes.
The basal families in the superfamily Trematopodoidea are the Tirghostidae, Trematopidae and Cochleosauridae families. All temnospondyls, for the most part, possess similarly configured lungs that are involved in the process of gas exchange. Less advanced forms had limited access to only one lung, whereas the most advanced forms had access to both lungs.

Originally, temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae. Early forms, with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements, were placed in the suborder Rachitomi, and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli. With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous forms is unclear. The great majority of stereospondyls, although in general quite distinct from temnospondyls, are probably stereospondyls.
